The fact that the order of these sentences does not in any way correspond to that of those in the original speech would show that Tacitus, in that process of adaptation to his narrative which he describes by the word ‘invertere '‚² considered himself fully at liberty to rearrange as well as to condense, and to give the arguments in what seems to him to be their most appropriate form and order.

The style and expression is thus his own, and the tedious antiquarian pedantry os Claudius is just sufficiently suggested to make the speech characteristic without being wearisome.
